","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cumberland) and Scottish (Dumfriesshire): variant of   Carlisle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlisle","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from the Cumbrian city of Carlisle, in whose name Celtic <i>cair</i> ‘fort’ has been compounded with the Romano-British name of the settlement, <i>Luguvalium</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Carlyle the younger was born in 1243, in Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland as the son of William of Carlyle. He had at least 1 son with Sapientia de Bochardeby. He died on 25 June 1274, in Scotland, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1243–25 June 1274":"1243–25. juuni 1274","1243–1274":"1243–1274","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1247–1279":"1247–1279","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1262–1329":"1262–1329","1210–1278":"1210–1278","12 OCT 1262":"12. oktoober 1262","1285":"1285","1274":"1274","1262":"1262","1247":"1247","25 June 1274":"25. juuni 1274","1279":"1279","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","1210":"1210","1329":"1329","Leith,Midlothian,Scotland":"Leith, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Annandale District, Dum